<dl id="n53112a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53112a">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53112a"> 112(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> s of / Myles the Slasher, drops &lsquo;o&rsquo; <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53112a"><li>FW 99.24 </li><li><a href="../../flex/d/lexd.htm#n53112a">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/d/l39d.htm#n53112a">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n53112a">MS BL 47476a-202</ms> </li><li>JJA 49:425 <a name="dd10" href="../../ff/fdra/dda.htm#dd10">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/d/dd10.htm#n53112a">Draft: I.4&sect;1.10</a>/2.10</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">&ldquo;This name <font color="green">[O&apos;Reilly]</font> is more usually given with the prefix &lsquo;O&rsquo; and it is said that a <mark>son of</mark> the family &lsquo;<mark>Myles the Slasher</mark>&rsquo; O&apos;Reilly &mdash; one Colonel John &mdash; <mark>was the first to drop the distinctive prefix</mark>, but it is, as said, more generally used than Reilly in these times.&rdquo; <font color="green">[O&apos;Donovan, writing in a footnote to the <i>Annals of the Four Masters</i> vi 2240, identifies Myles the Slasher with one Maelmora O&apos;Reilly, third in descent from Edmund, the last great chief of Breifne. Myles, he relates (perhaps fictitiously) was slain on the Bridge of Finea in 1644, while heroically opposing a superior body of Scots.]</font> <small> &ldquo;Irish Family Names: O'Reilly&rdquo;, <a name="WIT21jan33" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#WIT21jan33"><cite title="source">Weekly Irish Times</cite></a> (21 January 1933) 4</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
